      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>565</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000Z</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000Z.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Convergence in norm">Convergence in norm</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>In a normed vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, ||\cdot ||)]]></fr:tex>, a sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_n\}]]></fr:tex> is said to converge in norm to an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> if:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lim _{n \to  \infty } ||x_n - x|| = 0]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>This is also called strong convergence to distinguish it from other types of convergence such as <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000Y.xml" addr="FA-000Y" title="Weak Convergence">weak convergence</fr:link> or <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0010.xml" addr="FA-0010" title="Pointwise Convergence">pointwise convergence</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Convergence in norm has the following properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>The limit is unique</fr:li>
<fr:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n \to  x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y_n \to  y]]></fr:tex> in norm, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ax_n + by_n \to  ax + by]]></fr:tex> in norm for any scalars <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n \to  x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y_n \to  y]]></fr:tex> in norm, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x_n|| \to  ||x||]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x_n - y_n|| \to  ||x - y||]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>In a complete normed space (<fr:link type="local" href="FA-000F.xml" addr="FA-000F" title="Banach Space">Banach space</fr:link>), every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000X.xml" addr="FA-000X" title="Cauchy sequence">Cauchy sequence</fr:link> converges in norm to some element of the space</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>567</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0010</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0010.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Pointwise Convergence">Pointwise Convergence</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A sequence of functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n\}]]></fr:tex> defined on a common domain <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> is said to converge pointwise to a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> if for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  D]]></fr:tex>, the sequence of numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n(x)\}]]></fr:tex> converges to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Formally, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n\}]]></fr:tex> converges pointwise to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  D]]></fr:tex> and every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists an integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N(x,ε)]]></fr:tex> such that:</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f_n(x) - f(x)| < ε]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \geq  N(x,ε)]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>Note that the integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> may depend on both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε]]></fr:tex>, which is a key distinction from <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001S.xml" addr="FA-001S" title="Uniform Convergence">uniform convergence</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Pointwise convergence is generally weaker than uniform convergence. A sequence of functions can converge pointwise without preserving many important properties of the functions, such as continuity, boundedness, or integrability.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>569</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000Y</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000Y.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Weak Convergence">Weak Convergence</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>In a Hilbert or Banach space, weak convergence is a generalization of the concept of convergence that is weaker than <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000Z.xml" addr="FA-000Z" title="Convergence in norm">convergence in norm</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_n\}]]></fr:tex> in a Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is said to converge weakly to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex>, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n \rightharpoonup  x]]></fr:tex>, if for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y \in  H]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lim _{n \to  \infty } \langle  x_n, y \rangle  = \langle  x, y \rangle ]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>In a Banach space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, a sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_n\}]]></fr:tex> converges weakly to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> if for every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001P.xml" addr="FA-001P" title="Linear Functional">linear functional</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> in the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001Q.xml" addr="FA-001Q" title="Dual space">dual space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X^*]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lim _{n \to  \infty } f(x_n) = f(x)]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>Weak convergence has several important properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Every strongly convergent sequence (a sequence that converges in norm) is also weakly convergent, but the converse is not true in general</fr:li>
<fr:li>In finite-dimensional spaces, weak convergence and strong convergence are equivalent</fr:li>
<fr:li>The weak limit is unique</fr:li>
<fr:li>A weakly convergent sequence is bounded in norm</fr:li>
<fr:li>The unit ball in a Hilbert space is weakly compact by the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001R.xml" addr="FA-001R" title="Banach-Alaoglu theorem">Banach-Alaoglu theorem</fr:link></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
